{{Refimprove|date=November 2008}}
[[File:HancockCenterBraces.JPG|thumb|The John Hancock Tower has visible X-bracing on its exterior]]
'''X-bracing''' is a [[structural engineering]] practice where the lateral load on a building is reduced by transferring the load into the exterior columns. 

X-bracing was used in the construction of the 1908 [[Singer Building]], then the tallest building in the world.<ref>{{cite book | title=A History of the Singer Building Construction: Its Progress from Foundation to Flag Pole | publisher=Trow Press | author=Semsch, Otto Francis | year=1908}}</ref>

Some skyscrapers by engineer [[Fazlur Khan]], such as the 1969 [[John Hancock Center]], have a distinctive X-bracing exterior, allowing for both higher performance from tall structures and the ability to open up the inside floorplan (and usable floor space) if the architect desires.<ref>Ali Mir (2001), ''Art of the Skyscraper: the Genius of Fazlur Khan'', Rizzoli International Publications, {{ISBN|0-8478-2370-9}}</ref>

